					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Colorado Cowboy Poetry Gathering to Honor Buck Ramsey</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 1-09-08</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/buckramsey2.jpg" align="right" width="150" height="195" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

											<tr>
							<td>&nbsp;</td>
							<td class="image-caption" align="right">Caption: Buck Ramsey, photo courtesy of the National Endowment for the Arts.</td>
						</tr>
					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p>The <a target="_blank" href="http://arvadacenter.org/on-stage/cowboy-poetry-gathering-2008--evening-performances" title="19th Annual Colorado Cowboy Poetry Gathering">19th Annual Colorado Cowboy Poetry Gathering</a> kicks off Thursday at the <a target="_blank" href="http://arvadacenter.org" title="Arvada Center">Arvada Center</a>.&nbsp; The event, which lasts January 10 through 13, features performances by cowboy poets from across the region, and from as far away as Australia (represented by poet Milton Taylor).&nbsp; This year&#8217;s gathering will honor the memory of Buck Ramsey.&nbsp; I&#8217;d not heard of him before, but according to the Arvada Center, he &#8220;profoundly influenced the writing and music of contemporary Western performers.&#8221;  
</p>
<p>
The <a target="_blank" href="http://www.kacv.org/history/cowboy/ramsey.html" title="website of KACV">website of KACV</a>, the public television channel in Amarillo, features a biography of Ramsey and a recording of one of his songs&#8212;he had a lovely voice, and on this song at least, a cozy, endearing delivery.&nbsp; Ramsey grew up in the Texas Panhandle, and as &#8220;a young man, he began earning a little money punching cows,&#8221; according to KACV.&nbsp; At age 25, he was thrown from a horse named Cinnamon, broke his neck and was paralyzed.&nbsp; He used a wheelchair for the rest of his life.&nbsp; According to the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nea.gov/honors/heritage/fellows/fellow.php?id=1995_12" title="National Endowment for the Arts website">National Endowment for the Arts website</a>, &#8220;with cowboy work no longer an option, Ramsey turned to writing to earn a living. He did freelance work for magazines and newspapers, and nurtured his interests in cowboy poetry.&#8221;  In 1995, Ramsey was named an NEA Heritage Fellow. 
</p>
<p>
According to KACV, &#8220;his poem, Anthem, has been called the finest single piece of literature to arise out of the cowboy renaissance.&#8221;  (If anyone reading this knows anything about this cowboy renaissance, please clue me in.)  Ramsey died in 1998 at the age of 59.&nbsp; His widow Bette will attend the tributes to him at the Arvada Center this week.
</p>
<p>
Meanwhile, in San Francisco, the board of the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.bookcritics.org/" title="National Books Critics Circle">National Books Critics Circle</a> will gather on January 12 to announce the finalists for this year&#8217;s awards.&nbsp; Several West Coast literary types are scheduled to participate in a panel entitled &#8220;The View From Here: Is The West Coast Driving American Literature?&#8221;  Well, is it?&nbsp; I guess I&#8217;ll have to stay tuned for the outcome of that discussion.&nbsp; Panelists will include novelist <a target="_blank" href="http://www.andrewgreer.com/" title="Andrew Sean Greer">Andrew Sean Greer</a>, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.calendarlive.com/books/" title="Los Angeles Times Book Review ">Los Angeles Times Book Review </a>editor David Ulin, Seattle book editor Mary Ann Gwinn, Entertainment Weekly book critic <a target="_blank" href="http://search.ew.com/EWSearch/ew/search/search.html?type=ew:Jennifer+Reese;" title="Jennifer Reese">Jennifer Reese</a>, and Ellen Heltzel of Portland&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://thebookbabes.typepad.com/" title="Book Babes">Book Babes</a>.
</p>
<p>
Have some regional literary news or events to share?&nbsp; If so,  <script type="text/javascript">
